04493nam a22007095i 9781487574109DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191992onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875741097 a10.3138/97814875741092doi  a(DE-B1597)536872  a(OCoLC)1102074861  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHV6626b.T56 1992eb 7aSOC0510002bisacsh04a364.3/732201 aThorne-Finch, Ronald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnding the Silence :bThe Origins and Treatment of Male Violence against Women /cRonald Thorne-Finch. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. How Bad Is the Problem? -- t2. The Effects of Male Violence -- t3. Why Are Men Violent? -- t4. A Critique of the Traditional Treatments of Male Violence against Women -- t5. The State Response -- t6. Responses among Men -- t7. Where Do We Go from Here? -- tAppendix 1: North American Pro-Feminist Men's Group Contacts -- tAppendix 2: Suggestions on Forming a Pro-Feminist Men's Group -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPolice statistics, government studies, and media reports all indicate that male violence against women is escalating. But very little has been done to understand the deep roots of the phenomenon. Until that happens, no means to eradicate male violence will be effective. To this end Ron Thorne-finch offers an incisive analysis of the causes of male violence against women, and places the issue in a political context. He argues that men’s emotional, physical, and sexual violence are all inextricably linked: to end the violence we must address the effects of academia, the family, the media, the military, the peer group, pornography, and sport in creating violent men. The women’s movement has played a pivotal role in breaking the silence about male violence and providing the political pressure to compel state funding for victim and offered programs. But Thorne-Finch argues that changes in the current state response are unlikely to occur unless more men take individual and collective responsibility for male violence. He provides a detailed examination of the responses among North American men in encouraging and resisting male violence against women. Male violence must not remain ‘just’ a women’s issue. Thorne-Finch calls upon men to become more active in the struggle to end it. In a skilful balance between clinical intervention, social analysis, and political action he offers both the professional and the layperson a way to proceed in the struggle to end violence against women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAbused women. 0aAbusive men. 0aSex role. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757410940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487574109423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487574109.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK